<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 THE KING OF CARDS by Robert Ward (Washington Square: $10; 324 pp.) . Ward's 
coming-of-age story has a rambunctious energy that is difficult to resist. When 
narrator/novelist Tom Fallon returns to his alma mater to receive an honorary 
doctorate, he recalls the tumultuous mid-'60s, and how he came under the spell 
of the improbable, charismatic Jeremy Raines and his "completely 
self-indulgent, wildly crazy, and yet deeply humanistic" entourage. A good 
editor might have curbed Ward's taste for scatological humor; like Jeremy, the 
results are simultaneously engaging and frustrating. 
</P>
