<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP EYE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Bruce Haring 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 MAN IN THE STUDIO: Michael Jackson, returning to music for the first time 
since he canceled his concert tour last year amid a sexual abuse investigation, 
will soon enter the studio to record some new songs -- but what they're for is 
anyone's guess. 
</P>
<P>
 One possibility is material to fill out a long-planned greatest-hits album.The 
last time Jackson entered a studio to record some new tracks for the collection 
-- which has been in the works for years -- he was so prolific he came up with 
his 1991 album "Dangerous."  
</P>
<P>
 "He's going in under the same circumstances," says a Sony Music source, 
referring to the open-ended nature of the sessions. "The only question is 
whether it grows any bigger." 
</P>
<P>
 Jackson spokesman Michael Levine confirms that Jackson will be recording some 
new songs "before too long," but declined to say when the sessions would begin. 
Bruce Haring 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
