<HEADLINE>
<P>
ENVIRONMENT: NOTES ABOUT YOUR SURROUNDINGS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Starr Ranch Trips -- There will be two field trips to the Starr Ranch Audubon 
Sanctuary next weekend. South Coast Audubon, a chapter of the National Audubon 
Society, will sponsor a trip there Saturday, and the Sea & Sage chapter of the 
National Audubon Society will hold a special bird-athon field trip to the 
sanctuary May 1. 
</P>
<P>
 The privately owned sanctuary, which is nearly 4,000 acres, is home to many 
bird species crowded out by urban sprawl, according to South Coast Audubon 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
 The South Coast trip begins at 8 a.m. A previous South Coast Audubon trip 
yielded sightings of western tanagers and lazuli buntings. Participants are 
asked to bring binoculars and field guides (and a lunch, if they wish to eat 
with the group at the sanctuary's picnic area in the citrus grove). Heavy shoes 
are a must; those going on the trip should dress for possible changes in the 
weather. 
</P>
<P>
 Donations will be accepted at the South Coast trip to help maintain the 
sanctuary and fund research done there. 
</P>
<P>
 The group will meet at the Lucky's shopping center parking lot at Plano 
Trabuco Road and Santa Margarita Parkway in Rancho Santa Margarita. 
</P>
<P>
 Access to the sanctuary is limited, so those who wish to participate are asked 
to carpool as much as possible. 
</P>
<P>
 The Sea & Sage trip will begin at 7:30 a.m. It is a special field trip that is 
being held in conjunction with the chapter's bird-athon events. 
</P>
<P>
 There is a minimum $25 donation for those who wish to participate in the trip. 
Preregistration is required; call the chapter office at (714) 261-7963. 
</P>
