<HEADLINE>
<P>
NORWEGIAN REACHES NORTH POLE ALONE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 He pulled a 265-pound sled on skis. He braved polar bears and temperatures of 
40 below zero. And after 52 days, Borge Ousland became the first person to 
reach the North Pole alone and unaided. 
</P>
<P>
 The 31-year-old Norwegian adventurer sent a pre-coded message -- "Expedition 
ended, want pickup" -- via satellite Friday, indicating his 620-mile journey 
was completed. 
</P>
<P>
 Others have gone to the North Pole alone, but always with the help of dog 
sleds or supplies brought in from the outside. 
</P>
<P>
 "I have been very hungry. I'm looking most forward to eating lasagna and 
having a shower," Ousland told Reuters news agency by radio from his tent on 
the North Pole. 
</P>
<P>
 Ousland, who built up fat reserves by drinking a glass of olive oil for 
breakfast every day for a year before setting off on his icy slog from Siberia, 
has not changed clothes or washed during the trip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
