<HEADLINE>
<P>
RICHARD NIXON: 1913-1994; INTERNATIONAL REACTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 JOHN MAJOR, British prime minister 
</P>
<P>
 He praised Nixon's "tireless work for a better understanding between East and 
West. He was a leading architect of the process which led to the end of the 
Cold War, and his judgement of international affairs was widely respected." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 JIANG ZEMIN and LI PENG, Chinese president and premier, respectively 
</P>
<P>
 "A politician with strategic long-term vision and political courage (who) . . 
. opened the door for a new era in Sino-American relations." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 MUON SAOKHAN, adviser to First Prime Minister Norodom Ranariddh and Second 
Prime Minister Hun Sen of Cambodia. 
</P>
<P>
 "Morally speaking, even if he did something bad while he has alive -- we never 
relive the bad things -- we only speak about his good deeds." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 BORIS YELTSIN, Russian President 
</P>
<P>
 "I am shocked by the death not only of an extraordinary man but also of one of 
the greatest politicians in the world. I became convinced that he was one of 
the first major world politicians who have understood Russia and understood 
what it was fighting for." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 YITZHAK RABIN, Israeli prime minister, who had maintained a close relationship 
with Nixon since 1966 
</P>
<P>
 "Israel lost a friend. I personally lost a personal friend." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 HOA VAN TAP, retired Vietnamese soldier 
</P>
<P>
 "We won't grieve over his death. But the war is over and he is dead, and, as 
we say, 'Although there is hatred, death is the end.' " 
</P>
</TEXT>
