<HEADLINE>
<P>
BILL TO BAN MALT LIQUOR, FORTIFIED WINES STALLS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SANDRA HERNANDEZ, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Legislation that would restrict the sale of fortified wines and malt liquor in 
South-Central and in certain parts of Northern California suffered a setback 
last week in the Assembly. 
</P>
<P>
 Assembly Bill 2698 was expected to go before the Governmental Organization 
Committee for a vote Tuesday, but the bill's supporters postponed any action, 
acknowledging that they lacked the necessary votes. 
</P>
<P>
 The bill is intended to strengthen the Department of Alcohol Beverage Control 
by beefing up the agency's authority to impose fines and enforce conditions on 
problem stores. The bill would also establish a pilot program that would 
prohibit the sale of fortified wine and malt liquor in South-Central and in 
downtown Oakland for a three-year period. 
</P>
<P>
 "The bill is still alive, but it's been very difficult trying to persuade 
rural representatives or those who have been unduly influence by the industry 
that this is a problem that needs to be addressed," said George Wiley, a 
consultant to the committee.  
</P>
<P>
 Under the proposal, the state liquor agency could limit stores' hours of 
operation, the type of alcohol sold and require security guards. The agency 
could also impose fines on store owners who do not comply. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm not really worried about the bill because I already have conditions 
placed on the store," said Hyok Kwan, manager of the Lucky Liquor Store at 1471 
Jefferson Blvd. "I don't know much about the bill, but I don't think it will 
help people here because they will just find another place to buy those strong 
wines." 
</P>
<P>
 A major stumbling block for the bill has been the proposed pilot program in 
South-Central and in Oakland, Wiley said. He said the bill's author, 
Assemblyman Curtis R. Tucker Jr. (D-Inglewood), is considering limiting the 
pilot program to South-Central in an effort to move it through the Assembly.  
</P>
<P>
 The bill will remain in committee until next month, when it is expected to 
come up again for consideration, Wiley said. Tucker introduced the bill in 
February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA042494-0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 035542 </DOCID>
