<HEADLINE>
<P>
THAT CRUSTY BATHROOM SCUM IS ACTUALLY A BUILDUP OF LIME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Special to The Times 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 That crusty scum around your faucets seems impenetrable. You've tried 
scrubbing, but it just won't come off. What is it? How can you remove it? 
</P>
<P>
 These household nuisances are buildups of lime, actually calcium oxide, which 
occurs in the earth's surface and is carried to your sink and tub through the 
water supply. It builds up on itself, forming a crust, when water puddles and 
dries around faucets and drain lips. 
</P>
<P>
 Lime can be removed by applying an acid-based cleaning product. The acid is 
phosphoric, in most cases, but may be even stronger in some products, such as 
hydroxyacetic acid found in the product Lime-A-Way. 
</P>
<P>
 Whatever cleaner you use, apply the product, let it sit, loosen the lime with 
a stiff brush or abrasive pad. Be careful not to scratch your faucet or 
porcelain -- only rub the caked on lime. Reapply as necessary, rinsing well 
between applications. For extremely heavy buildup, scraping or chipping with a 
blunt tool such as a butter knife may be necessary after the buildup is 
somewhat loosened. 
</P>
<P>
 Do not use these acid-based products in combination with ammonia or bleach or 
their derivative products, as toxic fumes will result. Read and follow label 
directions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA042494-0396 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 035559 </DOCID>
